  <main>
    <h1 class="text-center underline font-bold my-5">
      Investigating the effect that the mass of salt in water has on its
      specific heat capacity
    </h1>
    <h2>Research question</h2>
    <p>
      After an experiment in class, I found I was keen to explore the concept of
      specific heat capacity further. I thought that the link between the mass
      of salt dissolved in water and specific heat capacity would be interesting
      to investigate. Hence, my research question is:
    </p>
    <p class="italic font-bold">
      How does the mass of salt dissolved in water affect the specific heat
      capacity of the solution?
    </p>
    <h2>Theory</h2>
    <p>
      The specific heat capacity is a constant value existing for each unique
      material. It is defined by the amount of energy it takes to heat 1
      kilogram of that material by 1 kelvin. To calculate the specific heat
      capacity, one must measure the amount of thermal energy transferred into
      or out of a material of known mass. Often, this value is used to calculate
      the amount of energy required to change a material's temperature:
    </p>
    <h3>Equation 1</h3>
    <Math
      latex={String.raw`Q=mc \Delta T`}
      whereList={[
        {
          propertyAsLatex: "Q",
          value: "Energy in",
          unitAsLatex: "J",
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: "m",
          value: "Mass of substance in",
          unitAsLatex: "kg",
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: "c",
          value: "Specific heat capacity in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
        },
      ]}
    />
    <p>We can rewrite this equation for specific heat capacity:</p>
    <h3>Equation 2</h3>
    <Math latex={String.raw`c=\frac{Q}{m \Delta T}`} />
    <p>
      In this experiment, the magnitude of energy transfer is measured as the
      material cools when combined with another material of known heat capacity.
      We find the magnitude of this energy transfer by substituting the
      temperature drop of the known material into equation 1, then substituting
      that into equation 2. This produces the following:
    </p>
    <h3>Equation 3</h3>
    <Math
      latex={String.raw`c_{s}\ =\ \frac{m_{w}c_{w} \Delta T_{w}}{m_{s} \Delta T_{s}}`}
      whereList={[
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`c_{s}`,
          value: "Specific heat capacity of solution in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`m_{w}`,
          value: "Mass of material of known specific heat capacity in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`kg`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`c_{w}`,
          value: "Specific heat capacity of known material in ",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`\Delta T_{w}`,
          value: "Temperature change of known material in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`K`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`m_{s}`,
          value: "Mass of salt solution in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`kg`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`\Delta T_{s}`,
          value: "Temperature change of salt solution in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`K`,
        },
      ]}
    />
    <h2>Hypothesis</h2>
    <p>
      Equation 3 relates the specific heat capacity to the mass of the solution.
      The equation states an inverse proportionality between the specific heat
      capacity of the solution and the mass of salt in the solution. Given this
      relationship, it is expected that as the mass of salt increases, the
      specific heat capacity decreases at a decreasing rate. The graph of mass
      of salt against the inverse of the specific heat capacity will have a
      positive, linear correlation. Since a mass of 0 salt in the water would be
      distilled water, the graph is expected to have a y-intercept of
      <InlineMath latex={String.raw`4186 J \cdot kg − 1 \cdot K − 1`} />
      (Engineering Toolbox n.d.)
    </p>
    <h2>Diagram</h2>
    <img
      class="min-w-full"
      src="images/diagram.svg"
      alt="Diagram of the experiment"
    />
    <h2>Apparatus</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>1x hot plate</li>
      <li>1x 1000ml beaker</li>
      <li>1x test tube</li>
      <li>1x retort stand</li>
      <li>1x clamp</li>
      <li>2x analogue thermometer</li>
      <li>1x digital thermometer</li>
      <li>1x calorimeter</li>
      <li>1x computer with relevant software for thermometer</li>
      <li>0.05kg sodium chloride (table salt)</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>Method</h2>
    <p>
      Initially, I wanted to pursue an experiment that investigated specific
      heat capacity by heating solutions rather than cooling them down. In order
      to achieve this, I decided to place a heating element in the solution
      along with a thermometer. This method appeared sound to me until I had
      completed my control trial and began to use salt. I accidentally made
      bleach by running a current through the sodium chloride solution. I
      considered indirectly heating the water, however, I decided it is too
      difficult to heat and insulate water using the equipment in our school
      lab.
    </p>
    <p>
      I abandoned that method and decided on this alternative method that uses
      cooling to determine the specific heat capacity rather than heating.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Note the mass of calorimeter.</li>
      <li>
        Fill the beaker with water so that when the test tube is filled with
        25ml of solution and submerged in the water, the water level is above
        that of the solution.
      </li>
      <li>Place the beaker on the hot plate and heat to above 90°C.</li>
      <li>Fill calorimeter with 150ml of distilled water.</li>
      <li>
        Submerge the digital thermometer in the calorimeter and note the
        temperature.
      </li>
      <li>Dissolve 0.0005kg of salt in 25ml of water.</li>
      <li>
        Transfer solution into test tube and submerge test tube in water. Heat
        to 90°C exactly.
      </li>
      <li>
        Once heated, transfer solution to calorimeter quickly and start the
        digital thermometer.
      </li>
      <li>
        Watch the thermometer carefully and record its maximum temperature.
      </li>
      <li>
        Record the combined final weight of solution and water. Discard the
        combined solution.
      </li>
      <li>
        Repeat steps 4, 6, 7, 8, 9 for different amounts of salt, including a
        control trial with 0kg of salt.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <div class="border border-solid border-red-700 p-3 my-5">
      <span class="text-red-700">SAFETY PRECAUTIONS:</span>
      <ul>
        <li>
          The test tube is extremely hot after it is heated to 90°C. Use gloves
          and take care with the liquid.
        </li>
        <li>
          The hot plate is extremely hot. Stay aware of it and keep hands clear.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <h2>Variables</h2>
