    <h3>Propagation of uncertainty in specific heat capacity</h3>
    <p>
      Take equation 3, <InlineMath
        latex={String.raw`c_{s}\ =\ \frac{m_{w}c_{w} \Delta T_{w}}{m_{s} \Delta T_{s}}`}
      /> to be <InlineMath latex={String.raw`a=\frac{bcd}{ef}`} />
    </p>
    <p>Uncertainty in specific heat capacity is then:</p>
    <Math
      latex={String.raw`\frac{\Delta a}{a} = \frac{\Delta b}{b} + \frac{\Delta c}{c} + \frac{\Delta d}{d} + \frac{\Delta e}{e} + \frac{\Delta f}{f}`}
    />
    <p>
      However, c is the known value of specific heat capacity for water, so it
      does not need to be considered.
    </p>
    <h4>Example propagation for salt mass of 0.0005kg:</h4>
    <p>Find fractional uncertainty:</p>
    <Math
      latex={String.raw`\frac{0.0001}{0.15} + \frac{0.25}{28.58-18.9} + \frac{0.000002}{0.0255} + \frac{0.25}{90-28.58} = 0.03063321`}
    />
    <p>Convert to absolute and round to a single significant figure:</p>
    <Math
      latex={String.raw`0.03063321 \cdot 4196.310053 = 128.55 \Rightarrow 100 \: J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`}
    />
    <h3>Graph</h3>
    <img class="min-w-full" src="images/graph.svg" alt="Graph of data" />
    <p>
      This graph shows the mass of salt against the specific heat capacity. The
      graph is linearised according to the hypothesis. The error bars were used
      to create min and max lines of best fit.
    </p>
    <h2>Analysis</h2>
    <p>
      The hypothesis predicted that the graph of mass of salt against the
      inverse of the specific heat capacity will have a positive, linear
      correlation. The gradient of the main trendline on the graph proves this
      prediction. This trendline is valid since it passes through all the error
      bars. The maximum and minimum lines of best fit, while maintaining the
      positive, linear correlation, do not pass through the error bars,
      invalidating them. This is indicative of some random error in the data.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Best fit gradient: <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`0.0142 \: J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`}
        />
      </li>
      <li>
        Min fit gradient: <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`0.0104 \: J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`}
        />
      </li>
      <li>
        Max fit gradient: <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`0.0211 \: J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`}
        />
      </li>
      <li>
        Gradient: <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`0.0142 \pm 0.00535 \: J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`}
        />
      </li>
      <li>Gradient percentage uncertainty: 37.6%</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The gradient has a large uncertainty. This means the precision could be
      greatly improved. Despite issues with precision, the data does appear to
      be rather accurate since the points appear consistently close to the best
      fit gradient. There are two possible anomalies at 0.0025 and 0.003. The
      former sits below the average trendline shown by other points and the
      latter sits well above the trendline. Considering the error bars however,
      both points could reasonably sit on the trendline.
    </p>
    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      In conclusion, the mass of sodium chloride in a solution is proportional
      to the inverse of its specific heat capacity.
    </p>
    <h2>Evaluation</h2>
    <p>
      The design and method of this investigation was suitable for reaching a
      viable conclusion. However, the experiment experienced some systematic and
      random error that impacted the accuracy and precision of the data.
    </p>
    <table>
