          </td>
          <td>
            The conductor of experiment could control the stirring periods and
            ensure the solution is evenly heated by moving the thermometer
            around the solution before combining the soution and distilled water
            in calorimeter.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            The solution in the test tube sometimes had a considerable amount of
            time out of water as it was being transferred to calorimeter.
          </td>
          <td>
            Being out of the water meant that the solution could have cooled
            down, further invalidating the 90°C value used in calculations.
          </td>
          <td>
            The conductor of the experiment could move the calorimeter and hot
            plate close together to minimise the time out of water. The
            conductor could also consider some kind of insulation for the test
            tube. Alternatively, a second person could measure the temperature
            of solution before entering the water.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            Manufacturing defects or damage to the calorimeters was not examined
            when conducting multiple trials concurrently.
          </td>
          <td>
            While not visually apparant, I noticed that between trials the
            values of specific heat capacity would also vary with the
            calorimeter I used. This is despite the calorimeters being seemingly
            identical. This would add some random errors in the data.
          </td>
          <td>
            Do not conduct multiple trials concurrently. Only use one
            calorimeter.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            The calorimeter was cold for the first trial in each session that I
            conducted this experiment.
          </td>
          <td>
            Some thermal energy would be lost due to heating the calorimeter in
            the first trial. This would mean the final temperature value may be
            slightly lower for these trials.
          </td>
          <td>
            Warm the calorimeter with hot water before conducting any trials.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
